---
import BlogLayout from '../../layouts/BlogLayout.astro';
import '../../styles/global.css';

import { isBlogPublished } from '../../lib/blogGate';
import BlogCrossLinks from '../../components/BlogCrossLinks.astro';

const slug = Astro.url.pathname.replace('/blog/', '').replace(/\/$/, '');
const isPublished = await isBlogPublished(slug);
if (!isPublished) return Astro.redirect('/404');
---

<BlogLayout
  title="Best Scrabble Words with Double Letters — High-Scoring Doubles"
  description="Master double-letter words in Scrabble. JAZZ, BUZZ, FIZZ and more — score big with repeated tiles. Free strategy guide, no sign-up needed. Free guide."
  keywords="double letter scrabble words, words with double letters, scrabble double letters strategy, jazz scrabble, buzz scrabble, high scoring double letters"
>
  <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify({
    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "Article",
    "headline": "Best Scrabble Words with Double Letters",
    "description": "Master double-letter words in Scrabble. JAZZ, BUZZ, FIZZ and more — score big with repeated tiles.",
    "datePublished": "2026-06-15",
    "author": { "@type": "Organization", "name": "ScrabbleWordsFinder.com", "url": "https://www.scrabblewordsfinder.com" },
    "publisher": { "@type": "Organization", "name": "ScrabbleWordsFinder.com", "logo": { "@type": "ImageObject", "url": "https://www.scrabblewordsfinder.com/web-app-manifest-512x512.png" } },
    "mainEntityOfPage": { "@type": "WebPage", "@id": "https://www.scrabblewordsfinder.com/blog/best-words-with-double-letters/" }
  })} />

  <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify({
    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "FAQPage",
    "mainEntity": [
      { "@type": "Question", "name": "What is the highest-scoring double-letter word in Scrabble?", "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "JAZZILY scores 35 points base (without premium squares). Among shorter words, JAZZ scores 29 points and FIZZ scores 25 points. With a blank tile as the second Z, you can still play these words but at reduced value." } },
      { "@type": "Question", "name": "Can you use both Z tiles in one word?", "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "There is only one Z tile in the standard English Scrabble set. To play words like JAZZ or FIZZ, you need to use a blank tile as the second Z. The blank scores 0 points, so JAZZ with a blank Z = 19 points instead of 29." } },
      { "@type": "Question", "name": "Are double-letter words good strategy in Scrabble?", "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "Double-letter words are excellent when they use common tiles (SS, LL, EE, TT, OO) because the bag contains multiple copies. For rare tiles (ZZ, JJ), you need a blank, making them less reliable but still high-scoring when achievable." } }
    ]
  })} />

  <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-4">
    <article class="prose dark:prose-invert prose-gray max-w-none">
      <nav class="text-sm text-gray-400 mb-6 not-prose flex items-center gap-1">
        <a href="/blog/" class="hover:text-amber-500 transition-colors">← Blog</a>
        <span class="mx-1">›</span>
        <a href="/blog/strategy/" class="hover:text-amber-500 transition-colors text-gray-300">Strategy</a>
      </nav>

      <BlogCrossLinks title="Best Scrabble Words with Double Letters" />


      <div class="not-prose mb-8 flex items-center gap-3 text-sm text-gray-400">
        <time datetime="2026-06-15">June 15, 2026</time>
        <span class="w-1 h-1 rounded-full bg-gray-300 dark:bg-gray-600"></span>
        <span>7 min read</span>
      </div>

      <p class="text-lg leading-relaxed text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-300 mb-8">Words with repeated letters are some of Scrabble's most satisfying plays. From the legendary JAZZ (29 points) to everyday words like ASSESS and COFFEE, double-letter words offer consistent scoring opportunities — especially when those doubles land on premium squares.</p>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-amber-600 dark:text-amber-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-amber-400 pl-4">Why Double-Letter Words Score Big</h2>

      <p class="text-gray-300">When a high-value letter appears twice in one word, you effectively double that tile's contribution. And if either copy lands on a DL or TL square, the multiplier applies to that specific tile — potentially adding 20+ points to a single play.</p>

      <div class="not-prose my-6 p-5 rounded-xl border border-blue-500/30 bg-blue-950/20">
        <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-blue-400 uppercase tracking-wider mb-2">💡 Blank Tile Reality</p>
        <p class="text-base text-gray-200">The standard bag has only <span class="text-white font-medium">1 copy of Z, J, X, Q, and K</span>. To play JAZZ or FIZZ, one Z must be a blank (scoring 0). Common doubles (SS, LL, EE, TT) are far more reliable since the bag has 4-6 copies of those tiles.</p>
      </div>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-amber-600 dark:text-amber-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-amber-400 pl-4">Top Double-Letter Power Words</h2>

      <div class="overflow-x-auto not-prose my-6">
        <table class="w-full text-sm border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700 rounded-lg overflow-hidden shadow-sm">
          <thead class="bg-gray-100 dark:bg-gray-800">
            <tr>
              <th class="px-4 py-3 text-left font-semibold text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">Word</th>
              <th class="px-4 py-3 text-left font-semibold text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">Score</th>
              <th class="px-4 py-3 text-left font-semibold text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">Double</th>
              <th class="px-4 py-3 text-left font-semibold text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">Notes</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody class="divide-y divide-gray-100 dark:divide-gray-800">
            <tr class="bg-white dark:bg-gray-900"><td class="px-4 py-3 font-mono font-bold text-white">JAZZ</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-amber-400">29</td><td class="px-4 py-3">ZZ</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-400">Needs blank as 2nd Z</td></tr>
            <tr class="bg-gray-50 dark:bg-gray-800/50"><td class="px-4 py-3 font-mono font-bold text-white">BUZZ</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-amber-400">24</td><td class="px-4 py-3">ZZ</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-400">Needs blank as 2nd Z</td></tr>
            <tr class="bg-white dark:bg-gray-900"><td class="px-4 py-3 font-mono font-bold text-white">FIZZ</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-amber-400">25</td><td class="px-4 py-3">ZZ</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-400">Needs blank as 2nd Z</td></tr>
            <tr class="bg-gray-50 dark:bg-gray-800/50"><td class="px-4 py-3 font-mono font-bold text-white">JIFFY</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-amber-400">21</td><td class="px-4 py-3">FF</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-400">Both Fs available in bag</td></tr>
            <tr class="bg-white dark:bg-gray-900"><td class="px-4 py-3 font-mono font-bold text-white">DIZZY</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-amber-400">27</td><td class="px-4 py-3">ZZ</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-400">Needs blank as 2nd Z</td></tr>
            <tr class="bg-gray-50 dark:bg-gray-800/50"><td class="px-4 py-3 font-mono font-bold text-white">PIZZA</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-amber-400">25</td><td class="px-4 py-3">ZZ</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-400">Needs blank as 2nd Z</td></tr>
            <tr class="bg-white dark:bg-gray-900"><td class="px-4 py-3 font-mono font-bold text-white">FUZZY</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-amber-400">29</td><td class="px-4 py-3">ZZ</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-400">Needs blank as 2nd Z</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-amber-600 dark:text-amber-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-amber-400 pl-4">Reliable Double-Letter Words (No Blank Needed)</h2>

      <p class="text-gray-300">These words use common tiles with multiple copies in the bag — meaning you can play them without relying on a blank.</p>

      <div class="not-prose my-6 grid grid-cols-1 sm:grid-cols-2 gap-4">
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-green-500/30 bg-green-950/10">
          <p class="text-green-400 font-semibold text-sm mb-1">SS Words</p>
          <p class="text-xs text-gray-400">ASSESS (12), BLISS (7), CROSS (7), DRESS (6), GRASS (6), PRESS (7), GLASS (6)</p>
        </div>
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-green-500/30 bg-green-950/10">
          <p class="text-green-400 font-semibold text-sm mb-1">LL Words</p>
          <p class="text-xs text-gray-400">BELL (6), SPELL (7), SKULL (9), STILL (5), DWELL (9), SKULL (9), TROLL (5)</p>
        </div>
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-green-500/30 bg-green-950/10">
          <p class="text-green-400 font-semibold text-sm mb-1">EE Words</p>
          <p class="text-xs text-gray-400">GEESE (6), TEETH (8), CREEK (11), BREED (8), SPEED (8), FLEET (8)</p>
        </div>
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-green-500/30 bg-green-950/10">
          <p class="text-green-400 font-semibold text-sm mb-1">TT Words</p>
          <p class="text-xs text-gray-400">KITTEN (10), BUTTON (8), LATTE (5), ATTIC (7), BUTTER (8), OTTER (5)</p>
        </div>
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-green-500/30 bg-green-950/10">
          <p class="text-green-400 font-semibold text-sm mb-1">OO Words</p>
          <p class="text-xs text-gray-400">VOODOO (10), BAMBOO (12), SHAMPOO (14), TABOO (7), KAZOO (18)</p>
        </div>
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-green-500/30 bg-green-950/10">
          <p class="text-green-400 font-semibold text-sm mb-1">FF Words</p>
          <p class="text-xs text-gray-400">SCOFF (12), STAFF (11), BLUFF (12), CLIFF (12), STIFF (11), SNIFF (11)</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-amber-600 dark:text-amber-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-amber-400 pl-4">Strategy: Playing Doubles Effectively</h2>

      <div class="not-prose my-6 grid grid-cols-1 gap-4">
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/20 hover:border-purple-400 transition-colors">
          <p class="text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-purple-400 font-semibold">Premium targeting:</span> Place one of your double letters on a DL or TL square. The other copy gets base value, but the multiplied one compensates massively — Z on TL within FIZZ = 30 + 0(blank) = game-changing.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/20 hover:border-purple-400 transition-colors">
          <p class="text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-purple-400 font-semibold">Save blanks for ZZ/QQ:</span> If you draw a blank tile, consider holding it until you can pair it with Z to form JAZZ, FIZZ, or BUZZ. A blank-as-Z in these words is worth far more than using the blank for a common letter.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/20 hover:border-purple-400 transition-colors">
          <p class="text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-purple-400 font-semibold">SS as hooks:</span> Don't forget that SS words can be formed by hooking an S onto an existing S-ending word. PRESS → PRESS is already there, but PRESSES extends further.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/20 hover:border-purple-400 transition-colors">
          <p class="text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-purple-400 font-semibold">OO for vowel dumps:</span> Stuck with too many Os? VOODOO, BAMBOO, and KAZOO are legitimate plays that clear vowel-heavy racks while scoring well.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="not-prose my-6 p-4 rounded-xl border border-indigo-500/30 bg-indigo-950/10">
        <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-indigo-400 uppercase tracking-wider mb-3">📚 Dig Deeper</p>
        <div class="grid gap-2">
          <a href="/blog/best-q-words-scrabble/" class="flex items-center gap-2 p-2 rounded-lg hover:bg-indigo-900/20 transition-all group">
            <span class="text-indigo-400 group-hover:translate-x-0.5 transition-transform shrink-0">→</span>
            <span class="text-sm text-gray-300 group-hover:text-indigo-300 transition-colors">Best Q Words in Scrabble — maximize that 10-point tile</span>
          </a>
          <a href="/blog/best-z-words-scrabble/" class="flex items-center gap-2 p-2 rounded-lg hover:bg-indigo-900/20 transition-all group">
            <span class="text-indigo-400 group-hover:translate-x-0.5 transition-transform shrink-0">→</span>
            <span class="text-sm text-gray-300 group-hover:text-indigo-300 transition-colors">Best Z Words in Scrabble — ZAX, ZEP, and beyond</span>
          </a>
        </div>
      </div>

      <aside class="border-t border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-800 mt-12 pt-8 not-prose">
        <h3 class="text-sm font-semibold text-gray-500 dark:text-gray-400 uppercase tracking-wider mb-4">Related Articles</h3>
        <div class="grid gap-3">
          <a href="/blog/best-q-words-scrabble/" class="flex items-center gap-3 p-3 rounded-lg border border-gray-100 dark:border-gray-800 hover:border-amber-300 dark:hover:border-amber-700 hover:bg-amber-50/50 dark:hover:bg-amber-900/10 transition-all group">
            <span class="text-amber-500 group-hover:translate-x-0.5 transition-transform">→</span>
            <span class="text-sm text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300 group-hover:text-amber-600 dark:group-hover:text-amber-400 transition-colors">Best Q Words in Scrabble</span>
          </a>
          <a href="/blog/best-z-words-scrabble/" class="flex items-center gap-3 p-3 rounded-lg border border-gray-100 dark:border-gray-800 hover:border-amber-300 dark:hover:border-amber-700 hover:bg-amber-50/50 dark:hover:bg-amber-900/10 transition-all group">
            <span class="text-amber-500 group-hover:translate-x-0.5 transition-transform">→</span>
            <span class="text-sm text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300 group-hover:text-amber-600 dark:group-hover:text-amber-400 transition-colors">Best Z Words in Scrabble</span>
          </a>
          <a href="/blog/scrabble-tile-strategy-letters-scoring/" class="flex items-center gap-3 p-3 rounded-lg border border-gray-100 dark:border-gray-800 hover:border-amber-300 dark:hover:border-amber-700 hover:bg-amber-50/50 dark:hover:bg-amber-900/10 transition-all group">
            <span class="text-amber-500 group-hover:translate-x-0.5 transition-transform">→</span>
            <span class="text-sm text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300 group-hover:text-amber-600 dark:group-hover:text-amber-400 transition-colors">Scrabble Tile Strategy — Letters & Scoring</span>
          </a>
        </div>
      </aside>

      <div class="not-prose mt-10 p-5 bg-gradient-to-r from-amber-50 to-orange-50 dark:from-amber-900/20 dark:to-orange-900/20 border border-amber-200 dark:border-amber-800 rounded-xl shadow-sm">
        <div class="flex items-center justify-between gap-4 flex-wrap">
          <p class="text-sm text-amber-800 dark:text-amber-300 font-medium">🔤 Find double-letter words from your rack — free, instant, no signup</p>
          <a href="/" class="inline-flex items-center gap-2 px-4 py-2 rounded-lg bg-amber-500 hover:bg-amber-600 text-white text-sm font-semibold transition-colors shadow-sm">Open Word Finder →</a>
        </div>
      </div>

      
<h2 class="text-xl font-light text-amber-600 dark:text-amber-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-amber-400 pl-4">Building Your Word Arsenal</h2>

<p>The difference between a 300-point game and a 400-point game often comes down to vocabulary depth. Players who invest time studying valid Scrabble words consistently outscore those who rely solely on common everyday vocabulary. The words on this page represent a focused subset of the Scrabble dictionary that you can realistically memorise and deploy in competitive play.</p>

<p>Start by identifying which words on this page you already know. Then focus your study time on the unfamiliar ones — particularly those with high point values or unusual letter combinations. The goal is not to memorise the entire dictionary but to build a working vocabulary of 5,000-10,000 words that covers the most common game situations.</p>

<p>Consider keeping a word journal where you record new discoveries from each study session. Writing words down activates different memory pathways than simply reading them. Many tournament players carry small notebooks and review their most recent additions during breaks between rounds.</p>


<h2 class="text-xl font-light text-amber-600 dark:text-amber-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-amber-400 pl-4">Applying These Words in Real Games</h2>

<p>Knowing a word exists and successfully playing it in a game are two different skills. The bridge between them is pattern recognition — training your brain to spot opportunities for specific words when you see certain tile combinations on your rack. This comes through deliberate practice rather than passive memorisation.</p>

<p>When you study the words on this page, visualise how they would fit on a Scrabble board. Which premium squares could they reach? What letters would they need to hook onto? How many tiles from a typical rack would they consume? This kind of active visualisation builds the neural pathways that fire automatically during timed games.</p>

<p>One effective technique is to take each word and mentally construct the rack you would need to play it. Then ask yourself: if I drew those tiles, would I recognise the word opportunity immediately? If the answer is no, that word needs more study time. If yes, move on to the next unfamiliar word in your list.</p>

<p>Tournament players often practice with a specific study goal — for example, spending one week focused exclusively on 5-letter words containing a particular letter pattern, then the following week on 6-letter words. This structured approach prevents the overwhelm of trying to learn everything simultaneously.</p>

<div class="not-prose mt-8 text-center">
        <a href="/blog/" class="text-sm text-gray-400 hover:text-amber-500 transition-colors">← Back to all articles</a>
      </div>
    </article>
  </div>
</BlogLayout>
